  {
    "text": "An apples‑to‑apples comparison between a continuous probability map and a discrete classification requires either converting both to the same data type or using evaluation metrics designed for probabilistic predictions.",
    "topic": "apples‑to‑apples definition"
  },
  {
    "text": "Direct overlay of a continuous probability surface with a discrete classification map without any harmonization step is not an apples‑to‑apples comparison because it mixes incompatible data types.",
    "topic": "invalid direct overlay"
  },
  {
    "text": "When a conversion rule such as thresholding is applied to the probability map, the resulting discrete map can be directly compared with a classification map in an apples‑to‑apples manner.",
    "topic": "conversion enables comparison"
  },
  {
    "text": "Probabilistic evaluation metrics (e.g., Brier score, logarithmic score) allow apples‑to‑apples comparison of a continuous probability map to a discrete classification without thresholding.",
    "topic": "probabilistic metrics alternative"
  }
]
